<br>
More subtle ideas, though, can also help.  The way you light the mask can make a difference.  Dark is sad, light is happy, you know the drill.  Another thought that occurs to me is the position and angle of the head.  This sort of skirts the line between facial expression and body language, but in any case I think you could communicate a lot with it.<br>
<br>
Not sure what else to say without knowing more about the artistic style (if it's rather cartoonish, the mask could just change appearance to show emotion) and the shape of the mask you've got in mind. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/ufluxhavoc.showPublicProfile?language=EN>FluxHavoc</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://server2039.virtualave.net/xenoflare/misc/glowball.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Artist in Residence</span><br> <font color=#336699>(8/15/02 3:02:50 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=4209.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://server2039.virtualave.net/xenoflare/misc/thumb60.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Emotions under a mask?</span><hr size=1> Hands can tell a lot. But, the whole point of a mask is to hide emotions so....<br>
